 at the highest voltage for the device I tested it became even better than for the MCP-PMT in our setup, which is usually not the case. See the plot below.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"645\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/11\/Screenshot_2022-11-20_11-21-12-1024x645.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1013\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/11\/Screenshot_2022-11-20_11-21-12-1024x645.png 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/11\/Screenshot_2022-11-20_11-21-12-300x189.png 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/11\/Screenshot_2022-11-20_11-21-12-768x484.png 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/11\/Screenshot_2022-11-20_11-21-12.png 1296w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Signal to Noise Ratio distribution (<a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Empirical_distribution_function\">ECDF<\/a>) for the DUT and also the MCP-PMT which is the trigger and time reference in our <a href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/the-robocold-beta-setup\/\" data-type=\"post\" data-id=\"944\">Robocold setup<\/a>.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>To conclude, just to mention that this design should be easily scalable to an arbitrary number of channels, as long as there is space in the board to put the components.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>So far, for all sensor studies, I have been using either a single channel active board (Santa Cruz or Chubut) or a multi channel passive readout board. Though this works, it is not ideal. Firstly, the passive readout board is not the best because usually the amplifier is installed as close as possible to the &hellip;<\/p>\n<p class=\"read-more\"> <a class=\"\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/chubut-2-board-prototype\/\"> <span class=\"s